title: Avoid cudaStreamSync at the end of Forward/Backward
body:
As ORTModule should match the behavior of nn.module, we don't need to explicitly introduce a cudaStreamSync at the end of each subgraph execution. 

**Addition cudaStreamSync at the end of forward**
As shown in the profiling result below, ORTModule run has an extra cudaStreamSync call at the end of forward section. This was introduced as the finalizing step for InferenceSession::PartialRun(). This behavior is copied from original InferenceSession::Run() code when we implemented PartialRun executor. 
However, PyTorch would automatically introduce cudaStreamSync if following CPU computation has dependency on a GPU tensor. In another word, ORT doesnt need to introduce this call explicitly. 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9906745/138220276-97592e36-01ff-42b9-bbf7-509db983895a.png)

**Warmup Patterns after cudaStreamSync** 
As we zoom in to the time segment following cudaStreamSync call, we can see a time window lasting ~4ms that GPU is barely utilized. As the tasks in compute stream are depleted with cudaStreamSync call, CPU needs to refill the compute stream from scratch. This resulted in the GPU starvation, as CPU is not able to launch the kernels fast enough, worsen by the fact that the scheduled kernels are short to complete (<10us). The starving situation is eventually relieved when a larger kernel kicks in, taking up >100 us, giving time for CPU to catch up with the scheduling work. 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9906745/138220373-5db5f14e-22f7-44f5-a1db-3d98e86daecb.png)

ORT's Reduction kernel uses cuDNN for non-FastReduction case, which is much slower than PT. This PR is to switch ReduceSum to use ATenOp instead of current ORT CUDA kernel.

ORT CUDA kernel:

ATenOp:

title: Contrib ops for TRT plugins: EfficientNMS and Pyramid ROI Align
body:
**Description**: 
Registers two new contrib ops for TensorRT plugins: [EfficientNMS](https://github.com/NVIDIA/TensorRT/tree/master/plugin/efficientNMSPlugin), [PyramidROIAlign](https://github.com/NVIDIA/TensorRT/tree/master/plugin/pyramidROIAlignPlugin) and [multilevelCropAndResizePlugin](https://github.com/NVIDIA/TensorRT/tree/master/plugin/multilevelCropAndResizePlugin), which are common operations in object detection networks.

**Motivation and Context**
- TensorRT plugins allow fused and efficient execution of common complex operations not natively supported by TensorRT.
- An ONNX graph that has been modified to use TensorRT plugins ops will normally not run in ORT because it fails graph validation.
- This PR implements contrib ops for these operations so that ORT accepts them, and the TRT-EP backend can execute them.
- Additional TensorRT plugins can be registered in the future by following this PR as an example.

body:
**Description**: Describe your changes.

Update attention_cpu_base.h to avoid bug if mask_data == nullptr.

By looking into that code, it checks `mask_data` is not nullptr several times in that function. However, it does not check it in that for loop, so if it's nullptr, it'd be filling output with a nullptr pointer, resulting in undefined behavior.

title: Improve transfered time from ort to torch
body:
**Description**:

backward method creates many gradients stored in one OrtValueVector. The ownership of the data is then transfered to pytorch. This process needs the creation of a torch tensor for every OrtValue. One transfer costs:

* an allocation to a DLPack structure in ort
* the creation of a capsule to hold it
* the creation of a tensor in pytorch
* the allocation of another structure in pytorch
* the copy of a DLPack structure

The changes proposes to remove the first two steps. The DLPack structure is allocated on the stack and reused for every element of OrtValueVector, the capsule is also reused to save the creation of one python object. The cost of the transfer back to pytorch is approximatively reduced by 30%-50%.

All conversions from OrtValueVector to tuple of torch.tensor should go through function `_utils._ortvalues_to_torch_tensor`. If there is no boolean OrtValue, the function is 30% faster than the previous implementation.

**Motivation and Context**
- Performance: method forward and backward needs to take ownership of tensors from pytorch and give owernship of output or gradient. When there are many tensors to process (> 100 hundred), this can take a few milliseconds. This process cannot be efficiently parallelized. It creates many python object in a short time and goes through the GIL many time. Parallelization is inefficient in that case.

The conversion of 10 OrtValueVector of 100 OrtValue currently takes 0.003257s and 0.000871s with these changes. Measures obtained with the following script.

```
import time
import numpy 
from onnxruntime.capi._pybind_state import (
    OrtValue as C_OrtValue,
    OrtDevice as C_OrtDevice,
    OrtMemType, OrtValueVector)
from onnxruntime.capi import _pybind_state as C
import torch


def create_ortvalues(device=None):
    if device is None:
        device = C_OrtDevice(C_OrtDevice.cpu(), OrtMemType.DEFAULT, 0)
    memo = []
    ovect = OrtValueVector()
    for i in range(0, 100):
        vect = numpy.random.randn(2, 10).astype(numpy.float32)
        memo.append(vect)
        ort_value = C_OrtValue.ortvalue_from_numpy(vect, device)
        ovect.push_back(ort_value)
    return ovect, memo

def to_tensor_loop1(ovs):
    return tuple(torch.from_dlpack(ov.to_dlpack()) for ov in ovs)


def to_tensor_loop2(ovs):
    return tuple(torch._C._from_dlpack(ov.to_dlpack()) for ov in ovs)

def to_tensor_vector(ovs):
    return tuple(ovs.to_dlpacks(torch._C._from_dlpack))



fcts = [(to_tensor_loop1, None),
        (to_tensor_loop2, None),
        (to_tensor_vector, None)]


if False: # ort device
    # How to create a OrtValue with device == 'ort'?
    device_ort = C_OrtDevice(0, OrtMemType.DEFAULT, 0)
    print(device_ort.device_type())

    def ov2torch_eager(ovs):
        return tuple(C.to_aten_ort_device_tensor(ov) for ov in ovs)

    fcts.append((ov2torch_eager, device_ort))

for fct, dev in fcts:
    # check
    res = []
    for i in range(0, 10):
        ovs, memo = create_ortvalues(dev)
        begin = time.perf_counter()
        fct(ovs)
        end = time.perf_counter()
        delay = end - begin
        res.append(delay)

    print("%s: size=%d %f" % (fct.__name__, len(memo), sum(res)))
    print(res)
```

title: QDQ tool modification
body:
**Description**: 
This PR makes two changes:

1. Add op_types_to_exclude_output_quantization for users to specify nodes to exclude output quantization.
For example, user can specify op_types_to_exclude_output_quantization = ["MatMul", "Add"]
The reason to do so is that in some cases, for example QDQ BERT model for TensorRT, adding QDQ for node's output may end up with worse accuracy. So, we don't recommend to add QDQ to node's output under such condition.

2. Add option to force QDQ appear as a pair when adding QDQ to weighted inputs. 
User can specify {'AddQDQPairToWeight': True} or {'AddQDQPairToWeight': False}.
In some cases, for example QDQ BERT model for TensorRT, QDQ should always appear as a pair.
For our quantization tool, we do quantization on Dequantizelinear's input to remove Quantizelinear as optimization for weights. Therefore, we need to disable this optimization.

title: Add DynamicQuantizeLinear to DNNL EP
body:
**Description**: Describe your changes.

enable dynamicquantizelinear operator in DNNL EP. This op is needed to increase operator coverage for quantized bert based models

additional changes:
  add debug log in EP for operator coverage. The logging is used to track operator coverage breakdown and debugging

  block gpu elementwise op with 5 dims or more. OneDNN has limited dimension support on GPU for elemenwise ops (relu,log,abs and etc). The change will make DNNL EP not claim capability to elementwise ops with 5 or more dimensions when in GPU build.

 support for scalar output. OneDNN's internal memory representation is limited to tensor. As dynamicquantizelinear outputs scalar, in order to allocate the correct output scalar data handle for onnxruntime, this change is needed.

Signed-off-by: Zhaoyang Wang <zhaoyang.wang@intel.com>


**Motivation and Context**

title: Avoid skipping some tests
body:
**Description**: After the ONNX update, some tests are getting skipped because they are using the opset version as -1 which prompts the OpTester to use the latest "known" opset while creating the test model. After the ONNX update, the latest "known" version for the ONNX domain is 16 wheras the "released" version is 15. These tests eventually get skipped because by default only the latest **released** opset is run in OpTester:;Run(). So, default the logic in the OpTester to use the latest released opset in case the test sets the opset version as -1. All tests run with this change and test coverage drop is avoided.

title: Make ORTModule serializable
body:
Models that make use of `torch.multiprocessing` or `python.multiprocessing` require the model to be serializable and deserializable. Currenlty `ORTModule` is not serializable because of some of some of its attributes.

This pull request makes `ORTModule` serializable by introducing methods ```__getstate__``` and ```__setstate__``` that drop and reconstruct non serializable/deserializable attributes respectively.
